@page "/admin-panel/getting-started"

<div class="page-container">
    <h1 class="page-main-title">Getting started</h1>
    <div class="page-desc">
        Install the necessary packages to start building with the Bit AdminPanel.
    </div>
    <section class="section-card">
        <h2 class="section-card-title">Create project</h2>
        <div class="section-card-txt">
            1. Install the AdminPanel Template from the NuGet package manager.
        </div>
        <div class="code-box">dotnet new --install Bit.AdminPanel</div>
        <div class="section-card-txt">
            2. Create a new project using the Template installed
        </div>
        <div class="code-box">dotnet new bit-admin</div>
        <div class="section-card-txt">
            Or create a new project with the Visual Studio.
        </div>
        <div class="image-container">
            <img class="image" alt="Create new project" width="1265" height="834" src="/images/demo/create-project-admin.webp" />
        </div>
        <div class="section-card-txt">
            3. Make sure the first line in the <span class="high-light-text">AdminPanel.Web.csproj</span> file contains the following value.
        </div>
        <div class="code-box">@("<Project Sdk=\"Microsoft.NET.Sdk.Web\">")</div>
        <div class="section-card-txt"><span class="bold-txt">Note</span>: By default, the current folder name will be considered as the solution name. If you want to choose another name, use the switch -n as below.</div>
        <div class="code-box">dotnet new Bit.AdminPanel -n [YourSolutionName]</div>
    </section>
</div>

